From: m5-linux project
Subject: [PATCH 3/N] chickens: Add M4 Pro/Max and M5 CPU feature stubs

Uses features_m4 as the starting point for all new chips — same as how
T8140 (A18 Pro) was added. The "XXX figure out what features are actually
available on M4" comment already exists in m1n1; M5 inherits the same
uncertainty. Feature flags will be refined during bring-up.

ADT cpu-node `compatible` strings verified from the 25F71 device trees:

  T6040 M4 Pro / T6041 M4 Max : E=apple,sawtooth  P=apple,everest
  T8142 M5 base               : E=apple,sawtooth  P=apple,everest
  T6050 M5 Pro                : E=apple,sawtooth  P=apple,everest
  T6051 M5 Max                : absent from 25F71 — assumed sawtooth/everest

Correction: the earlier "blizzard/avalanche" claim was WRONG (it came from
reading M2/M3 boards j493/j504/j514s by mistake). Every M3/M4/M5 SoC reports
apple,sawtooth (E) / apple,everest (P). blizzard/avalanche is M2; icestorm/
firestorm is M1. These ADT `compatible` strings are the Linux DTS core names
and are a SEPARATE namespace from m1n1's MIDR codenames (e.g. T8132 = Donan).

The chickens.c table keys on MIDR part IDs, not on the compatible string, and
m1n1 labels each entry by chip codename (cf. "M4 Donan (E core)"). M4 Pro/Max
and M5 codenames are not known from the ADT, so the labels below stay neutral.
MIDR part IDs remain XXX (patch 2/N) — cpu-impl-reg holds MMIO base addresses,
not MIDR values; obtain from `mrs midr_el1` on real hardware.

--- a/src/chickens.c
+++ b/src/chickens.c
@@ ... (after the T8140 Tahiti entries) ...
+    /* M4 Pro (T6040) — sawtooth/everest cores, codename + MIDR XXX */
+    {MIDR_PART_T6040_ECORE, "M4 Pro (E core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    {MIDR_PART_T6040_PCORE, "M4 Pro (P core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    /* M4 Max (T6041) — sawtooth/everest cores, codename + MIDR XXX */
+    {MIDR_PART_T6041_ECORE, "M4 Max (E core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    {MIDR_PART_T6041_PCORE, "M4 Max (P core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    /* M5 base (T8142) — sawtooth/everest cores, codename + MIDR XXX */
+    /* XXX: features_m5 struct needed once M5 CPU errata are known */
+    {MIDR_PART_T8142_ECORE, "M5 (E core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    {MIDR_PART_T8142_PCORE, "M5 (P core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    /* M5 Pro (T6050) — sawtooth/everest cores, codename + MIDR XXX */
+    {MIDR_PART_T6050_ECORE, "M5 Pro (E core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    {MIDR_PART_T6050_PCORE, "M5 Pro (P core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    /* M5 Max (T6051) — absent from 25F71; MIDR XXX */
+    {MIDR_PART_T6051_ECORE, "M5 Max (E core)", NULL, &features_m4},
+    {MIDR_PART_T6051_PCORE, "M5 Max (P core)", NULL, &features_m4},
